{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"310"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/310"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.5,0.37,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108395"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/310"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90785"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"6054"},{"type":"tags","id":"6292"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108395"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents complaining of a sore right elbow. He says he fell out of bed earlier in the evening. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears distressed and will not move his right arm. There is obvious deformity of the right elbow. He has a palpable radial pulse. X-rays are performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Backslab, sling and review in orthopaedic clinic","Closed or open reduction and percutaneous pinning","Closed reduction, backslab and review in orthopaedic clinic","Collar-and-cuff and review in orthopaedic clinic","Closed reduction and arm elevation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a supracondylar fracture proven on X-ray, which is a common injury in the 5-8 year age group falling on an outstretched hand. Management is dictated by the Gartland classification:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGartland I fractures are non-displaced - these are treated with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabove elbow backslab, supported in a sling\u003C/strong\u003E at 90\u00b0 flexion for three weeks. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGartland II fractures are minimally displaced but the posterior cortex is maintained - these are treated by \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction\u003C/strong\u003E under anaesthesia \u003Cstrong\u003Eand immobilisation in an above elbow backslab\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGartland III fractures are significantly displaced in 2 or 3 planes -  These fractures require \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed or open reduction and percutaneous pinning\u003C/strong\u003E to fix the bones in place. It is important to assess the neurovascular status after the procedure as the anterior interosseous nerve can be damaged. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fracture shown is a Gartland III, as the anterior humeral line does not intersect the capitellum and there is posterior cortical displacement. Even if this was a type 2b (no displacement but rotation) then it is likely that the treatment recommended would be percutaneous pinning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollar-and-cuff immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for any supracondylar fractures. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimple \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed reduction and arm elevation\u003C/strong\u003E without fixation risks loss of reduction and further neurovascular compromise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of supracondylar fractures is determined according to their Gartland classification."],"references":["Allen SR, Hang JR, Hau RC. Review article: Paediatric supracondylar humeral fractures: Emergency assessment and management. Emerg Med Austral 2010; 22:418-26. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20874821/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90785"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"310"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20076"},{"type":"media","id":"20077"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20076"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e1b707d-5df7-4eaf-87ab-44fd53f87c86.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e1b707d-5df7-4eaf-87ab-44fd53f87c86.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":563,"height":299}},{"type":"media","id":"20077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20077"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0944afd1-6d4d-4545-a8c8-1b5f4dcf01cb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0944afd1-6d4d-4545-a8c8-1b5f4dcf01cb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":439,"height":562}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90785"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"202